07711nam a22011655i 9783110198850DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013946513  a97831101988507 a10.1515/97831101988502doi  a(DE-B1597)34645  a(OCoLC)853267123  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP117.V57 2007 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a41900aVisible Variation :bComparative Studies on Sign Language Structure /ced. by Roland Pfau, Pamela M. Perniss, Markus Steinbach. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (403 p.) :bNum. figs.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v1880 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has been argued that properties of the visual-gestural modality impose a homogenizing effect on sign languages, leading to less structural variation in sign language structure as compared to spoken language structure. However, until recently, research on sign languages was limited to a number of (Western) sign languages. Before we can truly answer the question of whether modality effects do indeed cause less structural variation, it is necessary to investigate the similarities and differences that exist between sign languages in more detail and, especially, to include in this investigation less studied sign languages. The current research climate is testimony to a surge of interest in the study of a geographically more diverse range of sign languages. The volume reflects that climate and brings together work by scholars engaging in comparative sign linguistics research. The 11 articles discuss data from many different signed and spoken languages and cover a wide range of topics from different areas of grammar including phonology (word pictures), morphology (pronouns, negation, and auxiliaries), syntax (word order, interrogative clauses, auxiliaries, negation, and referential shift) and pragmatics (modal meaning and referential shift). In addition to this, the contributions address psycholinguistic issues, aspects of language change, and issues concerning data collection in sign languages, thereby providing methodological guidelines for further research. Although some papers use a specific theoretical framework for analyzing the data, the volume clearly focuses on empirical and descriptive aspects of sign language variation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 0aLinguistic change. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSign language. 4aGebärde. 4aTypologie (Sprache). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSign language.  alinguistic typology.1 aAlibašić, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCormier, Kearsy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendriks, Bernadet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrmann, Annika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHohenberger, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeson, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadolske, Marie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerniss, Pamela M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerniss, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfau, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfau, Roland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPyers